# LangGraph Agent Rules

## Architecture
- Always define a typed state schema for all graph state (e.g. `StateSchema` with Zod or `Annotation`)
- Use `StateGraph` for stateful agents, `MessageGraph` for pure chat (append-only messages)
- For **subagents**: use subgraphs — compile a child graph and add it as a node in the parent graph; pass state in/out via a clear contract
- Define clear node functions — each node should do ONE thing only
- Use `addConditionalEdges` for routing logic, never hardcode flow in nodes
- Always define an explicit `END` node — never let graphs terminate implicitly

## State Management
- Keep state minimal — only pass data nodes actually need
- Use `MessagesValue` (or the framework’s message reducer) for message accumulation in state
- Never mutate state in place — always return a partial update object from nodes

Example state with messages (LangGraph.js):
```typescript
import { StateSchema, MessagesValue } from "@langchain/langgraph";
import { z } from "zod";

const AgentState = new StateSchema({
  messages: MessagesValue,
  // other keys as needed, e.g.:
  // count: z.number(),
});
```

## Tool Use
- Define tools with clear names and descriptions (structured tool interface)
- Always bind tools to the LLM when calling the model
- Use `ToolNode` from `@langchain/langgraph/prebuilt` for standard tool execution
- Handle tool errors via `handleToolErrors` or try/catch — log and return fallback state

## Checkpointing & Memory
- Always use `MemorySaver` or `AsyncPostgresSaver` for persistence
- Pass `thread_id` in `config.configurable` for all stateful invocations
- Use `checkpointer` at graph compile time, not at invocation time

## Error Handling
- Wrap node logic in try/catch — never let unhandled exceptions crash the graph
- Log errors with structured JSON (e.g. for CloudWatch or your logger)
- Return error state keys so downstream nodes can handle gracefully

## Testing
- Write unit tests for each node function independently
- Use `graph.invoke()` in tests for deterministic final state; avoid `graph.stream()` for assertions
- Mock LLM and tool calls (e.g. runnables that return fixed responses) so tests don’t hit real APIs

## Code Style
- Use async node functions for all I/O-bound operations
- Type all function signatures — state input and returned updates should match your state schema
- Name nodes clearly: `callModel`, `executeTools`, `routeQuery`, `summarizeOutput`
